<item>
	<title>Julien Danjou: Using a Bluetooth headset under Linux</title>
	<guid>urn:md5:8592013a4ced2c719784de23bc96e096</guid>
	<link>http://julien.danjou.info/blog/index.php/post/2008/12/12/Using-a-Bluetooth-headset-under-Linux</link>
    <description>&lt;img src=&quot;http://planet.debian.org/heads/jdanjou.png&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;84&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; style=&quot;float: right;&quot;&gt;&lt;p&gt;… is a no.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;It just does not work. I mean, it does work if you want to listen to music using &lt;em&gt;mplayer&lt;/em&gt; in 8 KHz quality, but don't even think to use it to phone using SIP.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;I've first tested with &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bluez.org&quot;&gt;bluez 3&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt; which is part of Debian. It roughly work, but sometimes it stops working and you have to restart &lt;em&gt;hcid&lt;/em&gt;, or to clean its cache. Not very stable.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;I've then tried using &lt;em&gt;bluez 4&lt;/em&gt;, compiled from scratch. It works much better, i.e. I can run mplayer a thousand of times without having it stopping to work, but I'm totally unable to use it with &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.xs4all.nl/~mfnboer/twinkle/index.html&quot;&gt;twinkle&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt; or &lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ekiga.org&quot;&gt;ekiga&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;And I don't even talk about &lt;em&gt;ekiga&lt;/em&gt; still unable to set a custom ALSA output. I even try to hack it via &lt;em&gt;gconf-editor&lt;/em&gt;!&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;That's really a shame.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
	<pubDate>Fri, 12 Dec 2008 15:21:00 +0000</pubDate>
</item>
